mpile? Then again, I need to figure out how to keep it version-agnostic. A lot to weigh here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Defining Gradle configurations**\\n\\nI can set up a configuration called `jschSources` to include the dependency \\\"com.jcraft:jsch:$libraryVersion:sources\\\" and create a task for unzipping and compiling it into a jar using `JavaCompile`. Then I’m considering whether to publish it or simply use dependency substitution for the project, which sounds simpler. \\n\\nI could create a Gradle task named `debugJschJar` that would unzip the sources and compile them into `build/jsch-debug/classes`, then package that into a jar. But I’ll have to use `testImplementation files(debugJschJar)`, since `resolveTestedLibraryJars` only tracks resolved artifacts, not file dependencies — that doesn't have a module group or name, so it won't be tracked.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing debugging options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about making the runtime use the debug jar earlier than the original, so I can manually track the debug jar with line numbers. However, the report still includes the original. It seems like some original calls might not be reachable. I need to explore TrackDynamicAccess, which reports dynamic call sites statically from the path, to see if all the original elements remain unaffected. I should check the dynamic access output files for more clarity.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_WhfPYVgSuvpjzyWvLsQ4gfcf|fc_0270f4b9bb8643fe0169fba1c205b88191adb88355aec7c4a0", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/com.jcraft/jsch/0.1.27/build/native/nativeTestCompile/dynamic-access -type f -maxdepth 2 -print | sort | xargs -r -n1 sh -c 'echo ===$0===; head -20 \"$0\"'"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1074, "output": 882, "cacheRead": 72192, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 74148, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "t